BEGIN_PGML
An astronaut on the moon makes a running jump off a cliff onto a broad flat plain. The clifftop is [$hU] higher than the plain. Because of the slight upward jump, the astronaut's height from the plain, in meters, [`t`] seconds after the jump is [`[$f]\text{.}`] How long will it be until the astronaut lands in the plain?

[_]{$tU}{20}

END_PGML

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
When the astronaut lands, the height will be [`0\text{.}`] So we must solve the equation [`[$f]=0\text{.}`] Using the quadratic formula:

[```\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
t\amp=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\\
\amp=\frac{[$negb]\pm\sqrt{[$b]^2-4\left([$a]\right)\left([$c]\right)}}{2\left([$a]\right)}\\
\amp=\frac{[$negb]\pm\sqrt{[$discriminant]}}{[$a2]}\\
\amp\approx\frac{[$negb]\pm[$sqrtdisc]}{[$a2]}\\
t\amp\approx\frac{[$negb]-[$sqrtdisc]}{[$a2]}\quad\text{or}\quad t\approx\frac{[$negb]+[$sqrtdisc]}{[$a2]}\\
t\amp\approx[$t]\quad\text{or}\quad t\approx[$s]
\end{aligned}
```]

Only the solution [`t\approx[$t]`] makes sense in this situation. So it will takes [`[$tU]`] for the astronaut to land.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

